2026-04-16 12:18:18 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power Supply module internal wiring from battery positive terminal to PSU Output Cable (+) and to LED/resistor branch', 'Power Supply module green LED/resistor branch misconnection (LED anode and resistor negative left floating)'] hypothesis_explanation='All control-module indicators are missing, the lamp never turns on, yet the PSU front LED is reported ON. The latest observation shows that the battery’s positive terminal is not wired to any conductor, so no 12 V can reach the series chain or the load, explaining why no control LEDs or the lamp light. The PSU output negative is wired, but the positive is open. Additionally, the supposed indicator LED/resistor branch is miswired: LED anode and resistor negative are floating while LED cathode is on PSU (−) and resistor positive on PSU (+). This configuration cannot form a complete circuit across the battery and therefore cannot legitimately light. The only consistent explanation is that the PSU internal wiring is faulty: the battery positive is not connected to PSU Output Cable (+) nor correctly into the LED/resistor branch, and the LED/resistor network is misconnected so that any "on" indication is spurious. Correcting these PSU internal connections (bond battery + to output + and complete a proper LED+resistor parallel branch across + and −) should restore proper 12 V output and allow the downstream modules and load to operate.'
